1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,371
In this video series, we are going to go deep into mathematical logic

2
00:00:04,471 --> 00:00:08,259
to try to figure out what math is, and where its limits are.

3
00:00:10,933 --> 00:00:14,919
In the first video, we will cover syntax vs. semantics, define

4
00:00:15,019 --> 00:00:19,532
what a formal proof is, and the definition of mathematical structures.

5
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:25,485
In the second video, we will cover basic set theory, since theories

6
00:00:25,585 --> 00:00:31,202
are defined using sets, and yet sets are defined using a theory.

7
00:00:31,266 --> 00:00:36,017
In the third video, we will cover Skolem's paradox, showing how

8
00:00:36,117 --> 00:00:41,485
first order logic cannot fully capture or determine certain properties.

9
00:00:41,533 --> 00:00:45,797
In the fourth video, we will cover the deductive completeness of

10
00:00:45,897 --> 00:00:50,367
first order logic, providing a bridge between syntax and semantics.

11
00:00:50,466 --> 00:00:53,225
In the fifth video, we will see the basics

12
00:00:53,325 --> 00:00:57,445
of primitive recursion, decidability, and the Halting problem.

13
00:00:57,533 --> 00:01:00,329
Finally, we will cover Godel's incompleteness

14
00:01:00,429 --> 00:01:02,710
theorem and discuss its implications.

15
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:06,550
As a bonus video, we will cover non-classical logics, and

16
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:10,536
see how they give rise to different visions of mathematics.

